\textbf{\MakeUppercase{Part 3: Beams}}\\
Using a meter stick as a beam, set up the device shown below. Decide on (1) a mass to use for $m_2$ and (2) the angle $\theta$, which you'll have to measure. Also measure the distance from the pivot points to the point at which the two strings are tied onto the ruler. Adjust the mass of $m_1$ until the system is in equilibrium.

\begin{figure}[h]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics{./beam}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Experimental value of $m_1$:\\

How does your experimental value compare to theory? How important is it to consider the mass of the ruler?

To find out, sum the torques around the pivot point to find that
\begin{equation}
\sum\tau=m_1g\l_1\sin\theta - m_2gL\cos\theta-\frac{1}{2}m_sgL\cos\theta=0,
\label{tau}
\end{equation}
where $l_1$ is the distances from the pivot point to the the string connecting mass $m_1$, $m_s$ is the mass of the meter stick, and $L$ is the total length of the meter stick. To arrive at equation \ref{tau}, we assumed that the strings are massless and that the pulley is frictionless.

Dividing both sides of equation \ref{tau} by $g$, gathering like terms, and re-arranging gives
\begin{equation}
m_1 = \left(\frac{m_2+\frac{1}{2}m_s}{l_1}\right)L\cot\theta.
\end{equation}
If the ruler were massless,
\begin{equation}
m_1 = \left(\frac{m_2}{l_1}\right)L\cot\theta.
\end{equation}

Calculate $m_1$ both (1) using the measured mass of the meter stick and (2) assuming that the meter stick is massless.
